              childhood and schooling interventions that does not rely on
              arbitrarily scaled test scores as outputs and recognizes the
              differential effects of the same bundle of skills in different
              tasks. Using the estimated technology, we determine optimal
              targeting of interventions to children with different parental and
              personal birth endowments. Substitutability decreases in later
              stages of the life cycle in the production of cognitive skills. It
              is roughly constant across stages of the life cycle in the
              production of noncognitive skills. This finding has important
              implications for the design of policies that target the
